author: Slow Hand
message_content:
I like to swap drum samples too and have acquired a workflow built around quick auditioning and easy comparison. It sounds like you're using Ableton, so I'm going to talk in terms of Ableton.

First off, I keep all of my drum elements (kick, snare, hats, percussion) on separate tracks in Ableton. Right away, that might be a deal-breaker for some people, because they like to have the entire kit on one channel for ease of use or performance reasons.

Every drum channel gets a *pitch* device in fro

author: Slow Hand
message_content: I'll load up a few kick samples while my kick pattern is playing and then use the *pitch* device to transpose the MIDI note up and down to trigger samples inside of each cell:

author: Slow Hand
message_content:
Since I'm in *Drum Rack* tip-mode right now I can't resist sharing one last trick:

If you want to audition layering your drum samples you can use a *chord* device to quickly transpose through your second sample.

This is good when you've found the body of your kick and want to audition clicky/beater/top samples.

author: Slow Hand
message_content:
I'll do something similar with an *Instrument Rack* when it comes to pitched samples like 808's.

I'll load a whole folder of 808s into individual chains. Then I use a *macro* knob to control *chain selection*. This allows me to route my MIDI data to a different chain and play the 808 sample on it.

As we all know, 808 samples can come in all types of different pitches (C, C#, F, Bb, etc). I'll spend the time to transpose/re-pitch each sample so that when I play *middle C* on a keyboard the 808

author: Slow Hand
message_content: Once you've chopped your sample, right click the instrument and select *crop sample*. This will prep it for separation and the next step.

author: Slow Hand
message_content: Then right click again and select the new option *Slice to Drum Rack* or *Slice to new MIDI track*.

author: Slow Hand
message_content: And *voila!* Now all of your slices are still mapped to the same keys but you can warp and time-stretch them independently.

message_content:
Oh I'm just having fun. 

In truth, incorporating a full keyboard into my setup is a big ask right now. I have my MBP perched on a tiny desk and do all of my typing and control from there. To remove the MBP to make room for a new keyboard and mouse would require a serious ergonomic reconfiguration for me.

author: Adam Thein
message_content:
Ah I see - so the way to get around the delay compensation issue with Return tracks in Live is to disable the sends on the track you are printing to.

So you are routing the mix using a send to a Return Track, then on a new Audio Track you set the input to be that Return Track, right?  Then on the Audio Track you have set to monitor, be sure to click "Disable All Sends" and that should correct any Delay Comp issues.

Alright. Here's a good example of how I might employ an *Audio Effect Rack* in Ableton. It's the lead vocal track from a record I did. This particular vocal is very synthetic and grimy, so as you'll see I've got several effects layers going on:

The *Effect Rack* circled in YELLOW is my basic vocal sculpting chain (EQ/Comp/Etc). It's how I get my vocal into shape. I have all five plugins enclosed in an effect rack so that I can quickly A/B the chain to verify I'm making an improvement.

author: Slow Hand
message_content:
Here's one more common move that I use all of the time:

It's an effect rack that forks the signal into a *Dry* channel and a *Verb* channel. Doing so allows me to pan my verb and dry signals independently within a single track. I can then apply EQ, saturation and effects to my verb, narrow the image, and then blend to taste against my dry signal.
